6–Male":"1266–Deceased","1227–1289":"1227–1289","1252–1331":"1252–1331","1199–1250":"1199–1250","–Female":"Deceased","before 1225":"before 1225","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1305":"1305","1227":"1227","1225":"1225","1335":"1335","1235":"1235","1289":"1289","1266":"1266","1199":"1199","1331":"1331","1265":"1265","before 1252":"before 1252","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Forfarshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Forfarshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfarshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ogilvy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish:  see  Ogilvie  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ogilvie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Oglesby  , a habitational name from the barony of Ogilvie in Glamis (Angus), whose name is probably Pictish, of uncertain origin and meaning.","Irish: adopted for   Gilboy  ."]}]},{"name":"Patrick","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name of the apostle and patron saint of Ireland (  <i>c.</i>389–461 ), Gaelic <i>Pádraig</i>. He was a Christian Briton and a Roman citizen, who as a young man was captured and enslaved by raiders from Ireland. He escaped and went to Gaul before returning home to Britain. In about  419  he felt a call to do missionary work in Ireland. He studied for twelve years at Auxerre, and in  432  returned to Ireland. For the rest of his life it is difficult to distinguish fact from fiction. He apparently went to the court of the high kings at Tara and made some converts there; then he travelled around Ireland making further converts until about  445 , when he established his archiepiscopal see at Armagh. By the time of his death almost the whole of Ireland is said to have been converted to Christianity. He is also credited with codifying the laws of Ireland. In his Latin autobiography, as well as in later tradition, his name appears as <i>Patricius</i> ‘patrician’ (i.e. belonging to the Roman senatorial or noble class), but this may actually represent a Latinized form of some lost Celtic (British) name. In Ireland in particular, it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Patrick Ogilvy was born in 1225, in Forfarshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Alexander Ogilvy and Mrs. de Ogilvie. He married Marjorie Ossory before 1252, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1305, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 80, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"1225–1305":"1225–1305","1235–1335":"1235–1335","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1266–Male":"1266–Surnud","1227–1289":"1227–1289","1252–1331":"1252–1331","1199–1250":"1199–1250","–Female":"Surnud","before 1225":"enne 1225","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1305":"1305","1227":"1227","1225":"1225","1335":"1335","1235":"1235","1289":"1289","1266":"1266","1199":"1199","1331":"1331","1265":"1265","before 1252":"enne 1252","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Forfarshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Forfarshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfarshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1225–1305":"1225–1305","1235–1335":"1235–1335","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1265–Male":"1265–Kuollut","1266–Male":"1266–Kuollut","1227–1289":"1227–1289","1252–1331":"1252–1331","1199–1250":"1199–1250","–Female":"Kuollut","before 1225":"ennen vuotta 1225","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1305":"1305","1227":"1227","1225":"1225","1335":"1335","1235":"1235","1289":"1289","1266":"1266","1199":"1199","1331":"1331","1265":"1265","before 1252":"ennen vuotta 1252","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Europe":"Europe","Forfarshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Forfarshir